text: <@UJVF4N84Q> Thanks for sharing this amazing stuff with us, There are scenarios where the fast-cgi approach will fit better the requeriments of the applications, so it's nice to have this door opened.  About if it maybe be replacement of mod-harbour, maybe but my thoughts are that as the mod-harbour module is a very lightweight layout and  will be no penalty in keep the mod-harbour interface in the middle. I've an ISAPI module that I'm using with Xbase++ , and also an interface to use directly with server HTTPAPI   ( IIS itself is built as a client of HTTPAPI  ) and my plans are to build both components as an external  layout that will use the mod-harbour interface, so depending on the needs and the customer existing scenarios, we can use  mod-harbour below HTTPAPI or below an ISAPI extension. Maybe not so bad idea to  make fast-cgi also as another external layout  for mod-harbour. I have not dig enought inside your code to consider posible downsides of the approach I'm proposing, but will be nice if we can converge into mod-harbour

I have a question about loading order of libraries.   I found this:   There is two jquery libraries :
1. Core
2. UI
Thus , the order is :
1. Load `jquery.min.js` (core)
Then :
1. Import `bootstrap.min.js` (Where you have Carousel)
Then ,
1. `jquery.ui.js` (UI) (Where you have accordion)
Anyway, we recommend to wrap all your code when document is ready :
``` $(function(){

     // All your code here

 })```
